  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "To solve the limit \\(\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} (\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x)\\), we start by analyzing the behavior of the expression inside the limit as \\(x\\) approaches infinity.\n\nFirst, let\u2019s rewrite \\(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}\\) in a more convenient form for analysis. Notice that \\(x^3 - x^2\\) can be factored out:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{x^3 \\left( \\frac{x^2}{x^3} - 1 \\right)} = \\sqrt[3]{x^3 (x^{-1} - 1)} \\]\n\nWe can break this down further:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt[3]{x^3 (x^{-1} - 1)} = \\sqrt[3]{x^3} \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{x^{-1} - 1} = x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{x^{-1} - 1} \\]\n\nNow, consider \\(\\sqrt[3]{x^{-1} - 1}\\) as \\(x \\to \\infty\\). When \\(x\\) becomes very large, \\(x^{-1}\\) approaches 0. Thus:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt[3]{x^{-1} - 1} \\approx \\sqrt[3]{-1} = -1 \\]\n\nSo, as \\(x\\) approaches infinity:\n\n\\[ \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} \\approx x \\cdot (-1) = -x \\]\n\nNow, substitute this back into the original limit expression:\n\n\\[ \\lim_{x \\to \\infty} (\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x) \\approx \\lim_{x \\to \\infty} (-x + x) \\]\n\n\\[ -x + x = 0 \\]\n\nTherefore, the limit is:\n\n\\[ \\boxed{0} \\]",
